 "description": "Area: The borrow checker"}, {"id": 211668100, "node_id": "MDU6TGFiZWwyMTE2NjgxMDA=", "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rust-lang/rust/labels/T-compiler", "name": "T-compiler", "color": "bfd4f2", "default": false, "description": "Relevant to the compiler team, which will review and decide on the PR/issue."}], "state": "closed", "locked": false, "assignee": null, "assignees": [], "milestone": null, "comments": 2, "created_at": "2017-09-24T04:01:52Z", "updated_at": "2018-09-21T13:36:51Z", "closed_at": "2017-09-24T14:39:04Z", "author_association": "NONE", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "With the following program:\r\n\r\n```rust\r\nuse std::sync::Mutex;\r\n\r\npub fn main() {\r\n    let foo = Mutex::new(0u32);\r\n    \r\n    if let Ok(foo) = foo.lock() {\r\n        println!(\"{}\", foo);\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nI get the following compiler error:\r\n```\r\nerror[E0597]: `foo` does not live long enough\r\n --> src/main.rs:9:1\r\n  |\r\n6 |     if let Ok(foo) = foo.lock() {\r\n  |                      --- borrow occurs here\r\n...\r\n9 | }\r\n  | ^ `foo` dropped here while still borrowed\r\n  |\r\n  = note: values in a scope are dropped in the opposite order they are created\r\n```\r\n\r\nHowever when I modify the program as follows:\r\n\r\n```rust\r\nuse std::sync::Mutex;\r\n\r\npub fn main() {\r\n    let foo = Mutex::new(0u32);\r\n    \r\n    if let Ok(foo) = foo.lock() {\r\n        println!(\"{}\", foo);\r\n    }\r\n    \r\n    {}\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe program compiles and runs as expected.\r\n\r\nIt seems odd to me that inserting `{}` after the `lock` fixes the issue.  It appears that any code following the `lock` allows for the program to compile and run as expected, with an empty `{}` or `()` being the simplest way of doing this.\r\n", "closed_by": {"login": "Mark-Simulacrum", "id": 5047365, "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjUwNDczNjU=", "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/5047365?v=4", "gravatar_id": "", "url": "https://api.gith